        <div type="typology">
          <p>Western › Maghreb › Morocco</p>
          <p>Urban (prehilalien), sedentary dialect with bedouin influence</p>
        </div>
        <div type="general">
          <p>Basically, the dialect of Salé is almost identical to that of
              Rabat. The varieties of both cities were strongly influenced by
              the impact of Bedouin infiltration mainly in the second half of
              the past century and the large numbers of Berbers who settled in
              the outskirts in the same period.</p>
        </div>

        <div type="researchHistory">
          <p>By contrast to the old dialect of 
            Rabat (<rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:24WAIPFC zotid:YJK7X5S7 zotid:A3CUIZYB zotid:WT49QNB4 zotid:LKHVEAT5 zotid:Z67HNHBG">L. Brunot 1918ff.</rs>), 
            there exist no in-depth studies of the dialect of the medina of Salé. It can be
              assumed that the old dialect of Salé (as is stated for Rabat) had
              similar basic features as Tanger and Tetouan speech. The
              development from an „urban“ to a „mixed rural-urban“ dialect is
              described by <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:QEG433QR">Messaoudi (2002)</rs>. Recent grammatical and lexical studies on
              Rabat/Salé have been undertaken by <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:LMDE3E4E">Heath (2002)</rs> and 
              <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:CG324JCW">Behnstedt (2011-14)</rs>.</p>
        </div>

